      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Heads up: before you start any demolition, you must check local building codes and possibly get a licensed professional to verify the wall's load-bearing status. You can often tell if a wall is load-bearing by looking for a beam above it, a continuous foundation, or a thick concrete slab that runs along the wall. If you find a beam or a deep foundation, that wall is likely load-bearing and needs a header or support beam. If it's just a partition, you'll typically see a lighter stud frame and no overhead beam.\n\n**How to tell if a wall is load-bearing or a partition:**\n\n1. **Look for a beam or joist above the wall.** Load-bearing walls usually have a structural beam or a continuous concrete slab running along the top. Partition walls often have a simple stud frame with no overhead beam.\n2. **Check the foundation.** Load-bearing walls are anchored to a continuous foundation or a concrete footing. Partition walls may have a simpler, less robust foundation.\n3. **Inspect the wall thickness.** Load-bearing walls are typically thicker (often 8-12 inches), while partition walls are thinner (around 6 inches).\n4. **Check the building plans.** If you have the",
